Barack Obama is the fourth US president to receive the Nobel Peace Prize
The American President Barack Obama comes for 26 Hours to Oslo, Norway, to receive here as the fourth U.S. President in history, the Nobel Peace Prize.
He also receives the diploma, the medal and a cheque for 1.4 million dollars for his extraordinary efforts to intensify world diplomacy and cooperation among peoples.
Tomorrow, the White House boss will arrive in the North West metropolis with his wife Michelle and will be busy all the time.
First, he visits the Nobel Institute, where he meets for the first time the five committee members who elected him in October from 172 people and 33 organizations.
The presidential couple then planned a meeting with the Norwegian King Harald V and Queen Sonja.
In the afternoon, the visit culminates in the Obama prestige award ceremony.
He receives it as the fourth US president, but only as the third to receive the award directly in office.
The White House has already announced that Obama will speak about the war in Afghanistan when he takes over the prize.
The President does not want to evade this issue because he knows that he will accept the prize as a President who is currently waging war in two countries.
He stepped up the war effort a few days ago by sending more troops into Afghanistan, which none of his critics forget to highlight.
At the ceremony, Obama also received the gold medal, diploma and cheque for ten million Swedish crowns (approximately 24 million Czech crowns).
He intends to donate the money to charity, but has not yet decided on a concrete charitable work.
The programme of events will then include a banquet with the President and his wife, with the Prime Minister and another 250 invited guests, in addition to the King and Queen of Norway.
From the outset, Obama was very cautious about the price.
He argued, for example, that he felt he didn ’ t quite deserve the prize.
He also repeated several times that this is the price not only for him, but for all those who aspire to the same values as him.
Immediately after the announcement, he pointed out that for him this was an "invitation to action".
