USA: Repetition is mother of wisdom
It is almost comical to see Barack Obama, the president with his reputation as the wisest, repeat his predecessor ’ s strategy on the Afghanistan question, which he considered the most stupid.
When he finally sweated out his longingly awaited Afghanistan doctrine, it turned out that he copied it over the copy paper from the bush, Iraq, scenario three years ago.
Not only does he use the phrase "as in Iraq" several times in the text itself, he has even used the name of the January 2007 Bush Declaration as the name of his own declaration, "New Way Forward," without hesitation.
Three years ago, he himself criticised the Bush idea of sending fresh contingents of troops to Iraq plagued by the civil war as an "irresponsible and, in its conclusions, disastrous decision".
Subsequent months, however, showed that the Bush strategy, based on military recommendations, was the only one possible, and so far very successful, that the news about Iraq is no longer talked about at all.
This did nothing to improve Bush's reputation, because objectively he left his successor with a much more grateful starting point than was to be expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama hopes that the miracle will repeat itself.
The military, especially the commander-in-chief of Afghanistan ’ s Operation General Stanley McCristal, has again asked him to increase the contingent of troops, and he has harshly criticized the dithering White House shooters, despite the subordination habits.
He called for 40,000 soldiers to reverse the situation for the better.
The president hesitated for three months, but couldn ’ t come up with a better idea, so he betrayed the general by about 10,000 soldiers.
From Europe he pressed the promise for further 5.000, even if he originally expected at least 10.000.
Most problematic about Obama ’ s entire strategy is his plan to withdraw troops from Afghanistan in 18 months, and complete the process within three years. Obama ’ s entire doctrine leaves more questions than answers.
Some doubt that the halved increase will have the same effect as the measure in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal war of recent years, Iraq ’ s society is relatively well-structured, and its leaders honor its values.
The Afghan situation is characterised by contra-indications - no one can be relied on and no agreements are kept.
Under these conditions, it is difficult to prepare the Afghan security forces, which are used to changing their minds every day.
The political institutions, even if they were formally established correctly, remain only mock buildings, behind which the patriarchal master relations will continue to proliferate.
The balance of interests between the different ethnic groups is unusually complicated, especially because of the complexity of the circumstances that further complicate the influences of Pakistan and Iran.
It is also very unrealistic to build a "functioning state", which is the minimalist goal of the whole operation.
Obama ’ s time horizon of strategy alienated by his voluntarism
Over the last eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only deteriorated further and is now on the verge of explosion.
Believe that the little soldiers who have broken out into the war cry about the "early homecoming" can create a miracle here, can only a truly romantic soul, who does not let himself be impressed by facts.
From a political point of view, setting a date for troop withdrawal is sheer irresponsibility, because the Taliban will take it as the indirect confession of American defeat.
The latest NATO summit showed that Europeans ’ willingness to engage in the skirmishes in Afghanistan is waning.
Europe ’ s politicians cannot and will not explain to their voters how the security of Germany or Italy is linked to the war in the Hindu Kush.
Another possible factor that can radically influence the situation is the development of events in Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the increased sanctions do not affect the Iranians, the United States will face a very difficult question as to whether the problem cannot be solved with troops.
This question must be answered during America ’ s post-Obama departure from Afghanistan.
However, any solution will also mark a dramatic turn in the Afghan situation.
The only consolation for Barack Obama is the fact that there is still three years to go before the presidential election, leaving enough time for him to adopt another strategy, if it turns out to be a total failure.
