Czech discovery: a substance that also affects' steeled 'HIV viruses
The team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds to prevent the spread of HIV viruses in the organism.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also works on viruses that are already resistant to drugs.
This fact outweighs the disadvantage that the compound does not have as much effect on common virus variants as one of the existing drugs.
AIDS has not yet been cured.
However, the combination of drugs can prolong the patient ’ s life and prevent the spread of HIV viruses in the body.
However, their intake is accompanied by a whole range of side effects.
Incomplete suppression of the virus, propagation, also leads to the development of so-called resistant viruses, against which no medicines are effective.
The work of the experts from three institutes of the Academy of Sciences CR, the VSCHT (Chemical Technological University) Prague and the University of Heidelberg opens the way for dealing with the virus resistance.
They have demonstrated that the substances known as metalocarboranes act on the protein responsible for the proliferation of the HIV virus.
Metalocarboranes are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block virus replication in a different way than all drugs used today, so they can overcome the resistance related problem.
In their work, the scientists arrive at new 'improved' compounds that have been prepared on the basis of the knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to viruses, the protein.
The metalocarboranes have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multifarious cages consisting of boron, hydrogen and carbon, and coupled by a metal, an atom, in this case cobalt.
Treacherous and persistent virus
The HIV Protease is a protein of the HIV virus, which is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without the HIV induced by the HIV inhibitor protease, no mature infectious virus particles would emerge.
When we turn off the HIV protease, we also turn off the proliferation of the virus in the patient ’ s body, the scientists explain in the press release issued by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences CR.
In the work, which was published in the scientific journal Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, the scientists describe entire series of compounds in which two pairs of the cages (see table) are coupled by a short organic chain, which is then systematically further modified.
Slightly weaker but more reliable
The effect of these anti-HIV protease substances has been tested in a test tube, including against their resistant variants obtained from HIV infected patients.
The effect of metalocarboranes on the usual enzyme “variant ” is not as strong as that of clinically used drugs, but it does not lose its effect on the resistance variants against which the used drugs are often ineffective.
The unique mechanism of action and its other properties, such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of further chemical formations, make metalocarboranes interesting compounds for further research aimed at the development of effective drugs against HIV, says Pavlina Rezacova, head of the Structural Biology Laboratory of the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry and the Institute of Molecular Genetics of the Academy of Sciences.
