Vaccination against pneumococci free and voluntary
Vaccination against pneumococci changes the usual from January.
It should be the first to be free and voluntary for families.
But there are already voices saying that mandatory vaccination would be more effective.
Preparations for the introduction of free pneumococcal vaccination culminate.
The Pharmaceutical Institute already sets the maximum prices of vaccines that health insurance companies have to pay.
Experts are also aware of the vaccination process.
New vaccination
Vaccines free for August ’ s children
From January onwards, children born on 2 August last year and later can be vaccinated free of charge against pneumococci.
The condition is that they have not yet received a vaccination dose.
Anyone who has already started vaccination last year or earlier will have to pay for further repeat vaccination themselves.
The first vaccination dose must be given between the 3rd and 5th month of the child ’ s life.
Last year, a quarter of the families had their children vaccinated against pneumococci.
The parents paid 1600 crowns and more for one dose.
Four doses are required to vaccinate the youngest children.
On the whole, experts estimate that health insurance companies spend 300,000 to 450,000 crowns per year on vaccination doses.
But you save on the treatment that the children would need without vaccination.
So far, the state has spent about 500,000 euros per year on all vaccinations of children.
Mandatory vaccination was introduced with the so-called Janota-package.
Pneumococci cause middle ear infection, but also serious infections including meningitis and blood poisoning.
Due to pneumococcal infections, up to 28 children up to the age of 10 die per year according to an examination in hospitals.
Outside the Czech Republic, the obligation to vaccinate children against pneumococci has been introduced in about 40 countries.
Will vaccination be compulsory?
At the same time, it is said that this vaccination could be mandatory in the future.
Starting from January this is to be paid by the insurances and voluntarily.
For example, Rudolf Kalovsky, the head of the Nahlas civic association, mentioned that the obligatory vaccination would be better.
His association has been promoting the pneumococcal vaccine for a long time.
The experts at the international conference in which our association was involved were not very happy that we have voluntary vaccination.
This is not quite ideal.
On the other hand, we are pleased that we have succeeded in achieving at least that.
I believe that this is the way we must go now, Kalovsky said.
However, the Ministry of Health does not want to change the vaccination procedure against pneumococci.
At this moment we are not considering it at all, said his spokesman, Vlastimil Sesen.
Voluntary vaccination has its drawbacks, claim doctors.
The chairman of the Society of Pediatricians, Hana Cabrnochova, admits that voluntary vaccination has its disadvantages.
If all the children had been vaccinated, then one could think about reducing the number of repeat vaccinations. "In a situation where the vaccine is so expensive, we understand the political decision that this vaccination was started as a voluntary one," says Cabrnochova.
Experts expect that more than 80 percent of parents will have their infants vaccinated against pneumococci from next year.
The vaccination against pneumococci is also groundbreaking in that it is the first vaccination to be paid for by health insurance companies and not by the state.
The insurance companies should spend the money on prevention, thus saving them for further treatment, explains Cabrnochova.
Doctors have to buy the vaccines themselves.
However, this is connected with a concern of the practical pediatricians, which concerns the purchase of vaccines.
According to the original plan, the vaccines should be purchased by insurance companies, and doctors should then receive them in the same way as other vaccines issued to them by the state.
Some deputies feared, however, that the insurance companies could so "take out the money from the health insurance company".
That is why doctors will have to buy the vaccines themselves and wait for insurance companies to pay for them.
According to the estimates, individual general practitioners will have to invest 40,000 crowns per month, which is a significant sum.
It won ’ t be easy, says Cabrnochova.
