Can Islam be French?
Pluralism and pragmatism in a secular state.
At a time when Swiss voters have voted to ban the construction of minarets, and widespread concern about the alleged Islamization of Europe, John Bowen, an American academic, has written a well-founded and thoughtful report on whether Muslims can be integrated - and integrated - into one of Europe ’ s avowedly most secularized societies.
Some readers will read this new book out of admiration for the author's last work: "Warum die Franzosen keine Kopfftücher lieben" ("Why the French Don't Like Headscarves") (2006), an elegant and densely argumentative study of a controversial issue that divided and preoccupied the country over a decade and a half and whose effects can still be perceived today.
Bowen ’ s latest book offers a broader and bolder spectrum.
As a good anthropologist, he wants to know not only what politicians and the media say about Islam in France, but what is really happening in the field.
He spent months in mosques, schools and institutes, which now offer the 5 to 6 million Muslims in France, as Bowen calls it, "Islamic freedom".
He is a good listener, he reflects debates between teachers and students on the issues that concern them most.
Should a Muslim marry (or both) in a mosque or town hall?
Should young Muslims be taught about the evolution and rights of homosexuals?
Can a Muslim woman marry a non-Muslim man?
Is it permissible for a Muslim to use an interest-based banking system to obtain a mortgage?
It is these seemingly mundane matters, he claims, that make up daily life, in contrast to the political dramas that preoccupy the media.
The author recognizes a new generation of imams, teachers, and intellectuals, none of whom have a familiar name, with the possible exception of Tarik Ramadan, an Arab-born Swiss-Muslim scholar and academic.
This new generation is trying to open the debate on how to be a good Muslim on the one hand and a good citizen on the other in a modern secular society.
They do not have all the arguments on their side.
Conservatives are suspicious of the idea of French or European Islam.
The thinkers and activists who questioned Bowen mostly disagree with their Salafi counterparts - proponents of purist Sunni Islam associated with Saudi Arabia - who now have a small but influential presence among Europe's Muslims.
Bowen believes that Muslim values and French secularism may be compatible.
But an agreement requires give and take on both sides.
It questions the extent to which French policymakers (and the intellectual elite that so passionately guards the separation of church and state) are truly committed to pluralism.
He suggests that Muslims may be treated more harshly than Catholics, Protestants, and Jews, who in turn have had to make their historical compromise with secular republicanism.
He recognizes more a "tightening of the value screws" than a growing pragmatism.
Can Islam be French? After reading this book, one is inclined to say, "Yes, but not yet."
