The Arctic is changing faster and more dramatically than any other environmental region on earth.
The ice that marks her melts at an alarming rate, taking with it life that can't survive anywhere else.
Oil, gas, shipping, and fishing interests have moved into the newly open waters, with diplomats, lawyers, and now writers in their wake.
In "On Thin Ice" (original title: "On Thin Ice"), Richard Ellis, an author and illustrator, draws a natural history of the icon of the north, the polar bear.
Known for the complicated history and politics of whaling, he describes the long tradition of Arctic explorers who proved themselves in the polar bear hunt.
Admiral Nelson's encounter with a polar bear as a brave fourteen-year-old ensign at sea who fought only with the butt of his musket is certainly a legend, but others are true.
Young bears caught swimming behind the bodies of their recently killed mothers were taken to zoos and circuses.
A circus performance at the beginning of the 20th century showed 75 polar bears at one performance.
Even today, zoos still typically have one millionth of the habitat of a wild adult. The climate is rarely suitable: the polar bear in Singapore has become completely green from the algae that grow in the hollow hair of its fur.
Click here to find out more!
Ellis refers to the reports of other authors and historians and often returns to the threat that hunters pose to the survival of the species.
Although banned in Norway, America and Russia, the killing continues in Greenland and Canada, where hunters in helicopters and snowmobiles are using powerful Inuit assault rifles to hunt down their prey.
Ironically, the ice will last the longest in the northern waters of these two hunting nations.
In his new book "After the Ice" (original title: "After the Ice"), Alun Anderson, a former editor of the science magazine "New Scientist", offers a clear and disturbing description of Arctic science and a gripping insight into how the future could develop.
Not that scientists have all the answers.
Neither atmospheric scientists nor oceanographers can adequately explain the speed of change.
But that is not because of a lack of explanations.
The pioneer journeys of Fridtjof Nansen at the end of the 19th and beginning of the 20th century gave an idea of the swirling of the pack ice for the first time.
During the Cold War, submarines measured the shifting ridges of underwater navigation.
Satellite surveys and the large-scale deployment of probes on icebergs are a useful addition, but much is still achieved by intrepid people camping out in the cold.
Anderson takes a look at the peculiar, tiny world of the inflow system within the Arctic ice, which is formed by saltwater streams compressed during freezing.
But, from the bear on the ice to microscopic miracles in the ice, all are threatened when the summer ice passes, which is expected to happen between 2013 and 2050.
