Charleen Hunt, 70, from Westminster, said she made the trip to Arlington in memory of her husband, a late professional soldier.
Although her husband is not buried in Arlington, Hunt said this is her way of giving back to those who made sacrifices.
She said that this is a small contribution to how we civilians can support our soldiers.
It is like visiting a family tomb.
Wrapped up in warm clothing, the volunteers wandered across the vast lawns and hills of the cemetery.
The volunteers had older graves from the 1st and 2nd World War and the Vietnam War as a target, as these are not as often visited as the newer graves, according to the organizers.
The atmosphere was cheerful, children were playing and couples were holding hands as they carried the fresh pine branches to the gray gravestones.
Each round wreath was dark green with a small red ribbon attached to the top.
Section 60, which is located nearby and where mainly veterans of the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan are buried, remained almost calm.
