Some cried openly, others prayed, and families and friends held each other in the icy air.
Some read aloud the names carved in stone, while others leaned down to small black and white place cards that had been stuck in the damp mud for those whose gravestones were not yet finished.
Sandra Lockwood was one of the many mothers who shed bitter tears before her son ’ s grave.
She drove 8 hours from Zanesfield, Ohio, to visit the gravesite of Navy Corps Sergeant David Shane Spicer, who died in battle in July.
Nobody should ever forget why we are free... my son paid for it, she said.
