The news of the arrest was first reported Friday night by the New York Times.
The new US policy emphasizes that if the Cuban government takes concrete steps in this direction, such as releasing political prisoners and creating more space for opposition, the United States will provide something in return.
Mobile phones and notebooks are legal in Cuba, although they are new and sought-after products in a country where the average salary of a government official is $15 per month.
The Cuban government has only allowed ordinary citizens to buy a mobile phone since this year, and they are mainly used for sending text messages, as a 15-minute telephone conversation would cost a day's salary.
Internet access is extremely limited on the island.
It is available in expensive hotels and there for foreign visitors and at some government agencies, such as universities.
Cubans who want to log in often have to report their names to the government.
Access to many websites is restricted.
In Cuba, the arrest of an American is rare.
Most of the few US citizens in prison in Cuba are behind bars for crimes such as drug smuggling, said Gloria Berbena, spokesperson for US advocacy in Havana.
Berbena said she could not give any further information on the arrest.
The arrest and detention are clearly wrong.
An activity that would be legal in any other free society - the handing over of free mobile phones - is a crime in Cuba, said Jose Miguel Vivanco, head of the American section of the Human Rights Watch group, which recently published a tough report on freedom in Cuba entitled 'New Castro, same Cuba', an allusion to the inauguration of Raul Castro as the country's leader, replacing the sick elder brother Fidel.
