A gradual relaxation
enshrined in the country ’ s 1978 constitution, China ’ s A Child is arguably the most controversial decree adopted by the ruling Communist Party to date.
Couples who violate this policy face huge fines -- up to three times their annual salary in some regions -- and discrimination at work.
Chinese officials have attributed it to this policy that the critical use of the country ’ s natural resources could be avoided, whereas human rights officials have condemned abuses in enforcing the policy.
In rural areas, some officials have forced pregnant women who already had a child to have an abortion.
Many couples also had sex selective abortions, creating an unnaturally high ratio of men to women.
In recent years, government officials on behalf of the population have gradually weakened their stance on One Child Policy.
In 2004, they allowed more exceptions to the rule -- including city dwellers, members of ethnic minorities, and cases where both husband and wife were only children -- and in 2007, the tone of many harsh slogans was softened.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at the Department of Population Research at Beijing University, said that government officials have recently discussed even more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children with one partner as their only child.
Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to promote more births in July.
Posters that taught families to have only one child have been replaced almost overnight by guidelines detailing who is eligible for a second child and how to apply for permission.
The city administration has sent out city employees and family planning volunteers to visit couples at home and push through factsheets under the doors.
She also asked for psychological and financial advice for those who have more than one child.
The reaction was not very encouraging, family planning representatives said.
Disappointing reaction
Although officials from a small rural town in the outskirts of Shanghai said that there was an upswing in applications from couples who wanted a second child after the campaign was launched, the urban districts did not report any change.
The municipality of Huinan, with a population of 115,000, still receives only four to five applications per month as an example.
Disappointed Shanghai officials say that despite the campaign, the expected number of births in the city in 2010 will still be around 165,000 -- slightly higher than in 2009 but lower than in 2008.
Feng Juying, head of the Family Planning Committee of the Caolu Township in Shanghai, said that financial considerations are probably the main reason why many people do not want more children.
They want to give their best to their first one, she said.
Yang Jiawei, 27, and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26, said that they would like to have two children and that this was legally allowed.
But, like many Chinese, they have only marginal government health and life insurance.
Without a social safety net, they say, this decision would be irresponsible.
People in the West misjudge the A Child policy as a human rights issue, said Yang, a civil engineer whose wife is pregnant with her first child in the seventh month.
Yes, they deprive us of the opportunity to have more than one child.
The problem, however, is not simply a policy.
The problem is money.
Other couples give psychological reasons for their hesitation.
Wang, the HR manager, said that she only wanted a child because she was also an only child. “We were the center of the family and used to everyone taking care of us.
We are not used to caring for others and don't really want to. "
Chen Zijian, a 42 year-old who owns a translation company, put it bluntly.
For middle-class parents with double careers, which reduces the birth rate, he said, it is about being successful and for that you have to be selfish.
The 20- to 39-year-old age group grew up watching their parents fight during the early days of China ’ s capitalism experiment, and they don ’ t want such a life for themselves, he said.
Even a single child, he said, makes huge demands on the time of parents.
A mother has to give up her social life for at least two years.
Then there is the space question -- "You have to change your apartment" -- and the life plan -- "When the child is 9 months old, you have to have a CV ready for the best preschools."
Most of his friends are willing to go through this once, Chen said, but not twice.
Our generation is the first to achieve a higher standard of living, he said.
We do not want to make too many sacrifices.
United Nations Group Drafts Emission Reduction Plan
The UN-sponsored climate conference -- which has so far been characterized by wild poses and mutual recriminations -- has refocused on Friday with the publication of a document that sets out an ambitious reduction in greenhouse gases for the next 40 years, with the industrialized nations having to bear the brunt of the burden in the near future.
The text, which could provide the basis for a definitive political agreement on the regulation of greenhouse gases, showed both the remaining obstacles and the way forward.
But it was seen as an important step forward in a negotiation that is running out of time, as more than 100 world leaders will arrive in Copenhagen next week.
The text, drafted by a specially created UN working group, remains silent about the amount of money that rich countries should give to poor countries to cope with global warming in the short and long term.
It also offers a range of options on key issues, including how advanced and large emerging economies can limit their carbon emissions, and what the upper limit of global temperature increase policymakers would support.
The process will be highly flexible, said John Coequyt, Senior Representative of the Sierra Club in Washington.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who drafted the six-page document, has summarised a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what UN climate change leader Yvo de Boer has called 'the big picture'.
It outlines the blueprint for a possible agreement whereby developed countries would collectively reduce their emissions by 25 to 45 percent by 2020, compared to 1990 limits, while larger developing countries would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 percent over the same period.
Together, countries could reduce emissions by 50-95% by 2050.
The European Community has also given a boost to Friday's talks by pledging to provide US $3.6 billion per year over the next three years to help poorer countries adapt to the effects of climate change, from mastering floods and droughts to preventing deforestation.
Nevertheless, Friday brought the same verbal fireworks that dominated the talks last week.
American Climate Special Representative Todd Stern has rejected formulations that call for binding reductions in greenhouse gas emissions for developed countries, compared to voluntary reductions for larger emerging economies, if not financed by developed countries.
That train announced that the Obama administration is taking a tougher line with China than representatives of the Bush administration less than two years ago.
The United States will not sign an agreement without major emerging economies standing up and taking action, said Stern, who also complained that the text did not go far enough to ensure that the cuts could be confirmed by outsiders.
Stern made his statement one hour after Chinese Deputy Secretary of State He Yafei said that the leading American climate negotiator either lacked "reason" or was "highly irresponsible" about saying earlier this week that the United States would not financially help China cope with global warming.
With the future economic direction of the major world powers at stake, fault lines have opened up both within the developed world and between the developed and emerging economies.
The current battle is as much about saving individual economies as it is about saving the planet, with China and the United States fighting over their respective commitments, while poorer countries claim that the two dozen most influential countries would ignore the scientific need to take bolder action.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said it was not surprising that the major powers are fighting over who should bear the cost of curbing greenhouse gas emissions, as even affected countries have moved to be more aggressive in holding countries with very high greenhouse gas emissions to account for their actions.
This is clearly a game that will lead to a new economic hegemony, according to Ulate, who also serves as a regional climate change advisor to Conservation International in Mexico and Central America.
Some of the countries most exposed to the effects of climate change stated that they would continue to fight for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although the leading participants say that the talks will at best lead to a political agreement.
The Small Island States Alliance, with 43 members, presented a 24-page draft treaty early Friday morning.
Artur Runge, head of the international climate negotiations for the European Commission, said that the Small Island States' offensive "puts political pressure on the whole political process", partly because they are now united and demand action from emerging economies such as China and India.
The talks were given a new urgency as delegates focused on the fact that most outstanding issues had to be resolved before the arrival of government leaders in order to reach an agreement.
High-level officials, such as India ’ s Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and China ’ s Vice Minister of State, got out of their planes and rushed through the corridors of the Bella ’ Center for meetings behind closed doors and press conferences to chart claims to be negotiated over the next week.
The sheer scale of the gathering -- 13,000 people coming in and out of the Congress Center every day, guitar playing activists staging nightly shows mocking the countries they think are betraying and selling, and contract drafts being passed from hand to hand rather than e-mail -- is already challenging.
The intensity is only just building up: almost all the important ministers are now here and, from Wednesday, 60 government leaders will be in Copenhagen.
We come to the Oberliga, said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, vice president for global politics of the organization Conservation International.
The heavyweights are coming.
Britain ’ s first 225 km / h fast train redefines the feeling of the Monday
Monday morning at 5: 13, a pipe will penetrate the darkness to announce a train departure that is a revolution in traffic in Britain.
The first high-speed commuter train in the country will travel from Ashfort, Kent, to London St. Pancras at 225 km / h and travel 93 km in 38 minutes.
Lady Kelly Holmes will then go to Lord Adonis, the Minister of Transport, on board the first JAVELIN Commuter Service from London.
He hopes that the new service will eventually connect the UK to an international rail network of fast, reliable trains, connecting the major conurbations of the Midlands, the North and Scotland to London.
The neglected province could become vibrant commuter cities, working hours would be radically reduced, and changing planes and cars to trains would reduce national carbon emissions and road congestion.
In theory, the three major parties believe in this vision.
But the billions of British pounds needed to build a new national rail network, the inevitable planning battle, and fears of environmental degradation could still put the brakes on Britain ’ s high-speed railways.
High Speed Two (HS2), a company established in January to submit a feasibility study to the government, will present the report to Lord Adonis on December 30, according to The Times.
This will give him a detailed map of the next planned stage of the high-speed rail network.
The new rail line, which will connect London with the West Midlands, will have a five metre travel space and will pass through urban areas and places where environmental impacts are controversial.
In the open area, the plan will show the concept within a distance of 25 meters from the final route.
HS2 will also create three options for a larger, northbound, high-speed rail network.
Lord Adonis will respond to this in the spring.
The preferred option is a Y shape route, where a single high-speed line would lead to the West Midlands.
The route would split in or near Birmingham and one branch would run west of the Pennines to Manchester and Scotland and another to the northeast to Sheffield, Leeds and Newcastle upon Tyne.
A single line would lead to Scotland.
"It seems to be the best working option," said a railway insider.
Once completed, the travel time between London and Edinburgh would be reduced to 2 hours 40 minutes.
The first leg, which would not be opened before 2025, would allow travellers to cover the route from London to Birmingham in 49 minutes, compared to just over an hour today.
The designs would allow trains to travel at a speed of 400 km / h, making the British rail network the fastest in Europe.
The first line was planned in such a way that trains of 400 metres length with a maximum capacity of 1,100 people could travel on it.
Up to 18 trains per hour could be in service on the line from London to Birmingham.
This, in turn, would mean that a terminal station would be needed in London to handle 20,000 passengers per hour.
Given the limited space in the capital, it is expected that an existing station would be upgraded to accommodate the high-speed network.
Railway experts say that only St. Pancras International or Euston have this potential.
Lord Adonis will announce whether he believes this plan should continue or not, but the lengthy public deliberations and planning measures mean that a final decision will not be taken until after the parliamentary elections.
But even if it sets the wheels in motion, the rail network must be built in sections.
The trains would first have to change from high-speed lines to existing lines in the north of Birmingham, which would mean that the journey time between London and Scotland would continue to exceed three hours.
This is seen as a crucial sticking point to ensure a switch from aircraft to rail, a benchmark for the rail revolution.
Taxpayers Pay for Home Mortgage for £75,000 in Conservative Orangery
Alan Duncan, the leading Conservative member of the House, has charged the taxpayer thousands of pounds a year for the costs of an orangery that he had built in his constituency home.
The party's prison spokesman, demoted by David Cameron for complaining that members of the House of Commons have to live on "meager rations," has increased his mortgage by £75,000 to build an oak timber timber house on his second-home in Rutland.
He was allowed to charge the taxpayer the extra interest, a sum of hundreds of pounds per month.
The House of Commons officials approved the amendments at the time, and they were not questioned by Sir Thomas Legg, who is conducting a review of the House's expenditure. Duncan said last night that the amendments could not have been "cleaner or more comprehensible."
Duncan, one of the richest members of the House of Commons, owns a two-story house in a village in his constituency of Rutland and Melton.
Nearby houses have achieved a purchase price of nearly one million pounds (1.1 million euros).
The ground floor includes kitchen, living and dining room, but the Fees Office, an expenditure control point of the House of Commons, has agreed that Duncan needs more space.
Last year he added a conservatory, which is referred to in the plans as the "orangery".
Neighbours described it as a "greenhouse for entertainment".
Duncan was also not asked to comment on the increased borrowing during a recent investigation of his previous mortgage contracts by the Standards and Privileges Committee.
The committee acquitted him last month after an investigation into his expenditure.
In 2004, Duncan transferred the collateral for a £271,406 (300,000 euros) mortgage from his London home to his constituency house, which he bought in 1991, a year before his election as a member of parliament.
This week ’ s published documents show that by March last year Duncan was refunded about 1,400 pounds (1,500 euros) per month as mortgage interest.
In April, his claims rose to more than 1,800 pounds (2,000 euros) per month.
Duncan ’ s interest rate on RBS ’ s mortgage has not changed during this period, suggesting that the entire increase was used to finance the borrowing of £75,000.
The normal RBS stepless mortgage rate fell from 7.94 percent in December 2007 to 4 percent in March this year, where it still stands.
The latest documents released by the House of Commons show that Duncan continued to claim £1,250 (€1,400) per month this May.
Duncan lost his post as opposition leader of the House of Commons in September, after an undercover reporter filmed him saying after the spending scandal that members of parliament would live on "meager rations."
"Essentially, working for the state means living on lean rations and being treated like S * * * * * e."
He said, "I have spent my money on my garden and claim a miniscule share from what is proper.
And I could have claimed the whole damn sum, but I don't. "
The MP, a millionaire from his previous career as an oil wholesaler, was first attacked for spending in May, when it became clear that he had claimed thousands of pounds for his garden before settling with the Fees Office that this "could be seen as an exaggerated demand."
As a protest, an activist dug a hole in Duncan ’ s lawn in the form of a pound mark after it became known that he had demanded £4,000 (€4,500) over three years.
When asked about the increased mortgage last night, Duncan said, "This had been approved by both the Fees Office and subsequent Legg to increase value."
He added, "There is no debate about dodging and meandering or bending the rules or the like.
Everything is completely transparent and operates strictly within the rules, is approved and everything.
It couldn't be cleaner and clearer. "
Come to all you believers to admire Brighton's Beach Cabins "Advent Calendar"
Brighton beach huts have found a new purpose in life for the winter months as an interactive Advent calendar.
"Beyond", an alternative group of churches that encourages spiritual discovery through creativity, invited 24 owners to decorate their huts with Christmas carols as a theme for each December day.
The event started on the 1st of December and visitors could see the newest hut every day from 17: 30 to 18: 30 with free mulled wine and traditional mince pies, pastries filled with dried fruits.
The Christmas carols selected so far are "I saw three ships", "O come, o come, Emmanuel" and "The first Noël", whereby the hut decoration is the work of Janette Tozer, a local artist.
Martin Poole, 50, a TV marketing assistant from Hove, is an honorary clergyman from the Chichester Diocese and leader of Beyond.
He said, "We want to make religion more important for people in a post-Christian society.
Why do we as a church expect people to come into a strange old building? I think the church should go out to the people and have inspiring celebrations.
The idea of the beach hut, Advent calendar began as a conversation with some friends at dinner.
Brighton is such a fantastically creative and vibrant place and we try to express this through our spirituality. "
Strong mobilization in Copenhagen and around the world for the climate.
Tens of thousands of people demonstrated around the world and in Copenhagen on Saturday to demand an ambitious and binding agreement on the fight against global warming, where the police made several hundred arrests.
At least thirty thousand people, according to the police, a hundred thousand according to the organisers, marched in the cold of the Danish capital, on the fringes of the United Nations Climate Change Conference, which was supposed to conclude by Friday and which could take effect from 2013.
For Connie Hedegaard, Danish chair of the climate conference, the increasing mobilization in the world for the climate contributes to this, which is illustrated by these demonstrations that the "political price" of a failure in Copenhagen would be very high.
The incidents in the Danish capital took place shortly after the train passed, when a group of 300 demonstrators, dressed all in black, smashed shop windows with cobblestones and hammers, according to an AFP journalist.
Anti-unrest police officers have intervened immediately and without consideration.
The police have announced that 600 to 700 people, according to your assessment mainly members of the Black Bloc, this extremely violent splinter group that has already made a name for itself at the NATO summit in Strasbourg, have been arrested in eastern France in April.
The Climate Justice Action (CJA) coalition, one of the organizers of the demonstration, sharply criticized the conditions under which hundreds of militant supporters were arrested "without distinction," and pointed out that about a hundred of them "were still held in the streets on Saturday evening," despite the extreme cold with handcuffs and sitting position.
The rather peaceful train went from Parliament to the Bella Centre, where the negotiations took place.
The demonstrators stopped about 500 meters from the building without trying to enter.
A stage was installed to welcome the designated speakers for an evening of candlelight, with the participation of the former South African Archbishop, Desmond Tutu.
The majority of the demonstrators came with buses and trains from the big European cities, but also many Asians, among them some Chinese and Koreans, as well as some Africans were present.
Approximately 3,000 people, most of them wearing sky-blue raincoats, have made their first appearance in the morning in Copenhagen, as they have responded to the call of the Friends of the Earth "to make blue tides" for "climate justice".
Today we are taking to the streets to demand reparation for ecological guilt in favor of the South, said Lidy Nacpil, a Filipino activist for the Jubilee South Coalition in Copenhagen.
We can ’ t carry on like this and say to ourselves: we have time, said Angelique Kidjo, singer from Benin.
There are rivers in Africa that dry up, watercourses where you can walk like never before.
For the first time in the history of climate diplomacy, established in 1992 with the adoption of the UN Agreement, the movement of globalization critics has moved closer to environmental organizations.
José Bové MEP, the figure of the globalisation critics, announced that he came to Copenhagen to combine "climate justice and social justice": "Today there is no difference between the fight against global warming and the fight for another world."
The Asia-Pacific region, where many islands are located that are particularly vulnerable to warming, has launched the demonstrations.
According to the organisers, about 50,000 people have taken to the streets in Australia.
In Manila there were several hundreds of people, mostly students, who marched in red and hoisted bandanas in which they praised solar energy.
In Hong Kong or in Jakarta, but also in Canada, marches were held by several hundred demonstrators to demand a vigorous approach to climate change.
In France, the demonstrations organized by the network "350" have gathered several hundred people, namely in Paris, in Marseille (south), in Lille (north), in Bordeaux (west) and in Lyon (east).
Some people gathered in Geneva.
The separatist Abkhazia has elected its president, Georgia denounces that this is a "prank".
Abkhazia elected its president on Saturday, a little more than a year after Moscow recognised this separatist Georgian territory, which is pro-Russian, as independent, Tbilisi denounced the "coup".
Approximately 131,000 people were called upon to take part in the first election after the August 2008 Georgian war for control of the South Ossetian territory, another Georgian secessionist territory recognized by Russia.
The polling stations will be closed at 17: 00 GMT.
The turnout was about 58% a few hours before the local elections were closed, according to the Abkhaz electoral commission.
The first preliminary results should be announced during the night from Saturday to Sunday.
The five candidates, including the previous president, Serguei Bagapch, categorically reject the idea of reunification with Georgia, which condemns the election.
These elections are a farce.
For his part, Georgian President Mikheil Saakachvili repents that Abkhazia is now under total Russian occupation, according to his spokesperson, Manana Manjgaladze.
Apart from Russia, only Nicaragua and Venezuela have recognized the independence of this area with 216,000 inhabitants, while the rest of the world perceives it as a part of Georgia that is legally occupied by Russia.
After separating from Georgia during the 1992-1993 conflict, with the deaths of several thousands of people, Abkhazia wants to demonstrate through this election that it is ready to join the international community.
This process is a stage in our new life, a new era, as an independent state, Svetlana Kvartchia, a 54 year old historian, who claims to have elected Mr. Bagapch, explained.
She was one of the voters who went to vote at a polling station in a school in the capital, Soukhoumi, a beautiful white building with a few palm trees in front of the entrance.
The question of Russian dominance is at the heart of this presidential election, in a region with beautiful landscapes by the Black Sea.
Large signs on which Bagapch is to be seen at the side of the Russian president and the head of government, Dmitri Medvedev and Vladimir Putin, are everywhere in this small area that has 216,000 inhabitants.
In Gali, located in the east of the country, the district chief, Beslan Archba, has prepared a warm welcome to the Russian representatives who have come to supervise the election.
We, the people of Abkhazia, are grateful, he said at a small celebration, as an allusion to the support of Moscow, particularly with regard to the decision to recognise Abkhazia's independence.
I hope that your country will soon be recognised by the United Nations, replied Alexei Ostrovski, a member of the Russian Parliament, raising a glass of vodka.
For its part, the opposition, represented by the former vice-president and two Russian businessmen, Zaous Ardzinba and Beslan Boutba, has criticized the agreements made with Moscow last year, in which Abkhazia cedes control of the railways to Russia for ten years.
The fifth candidate, Vitali Banba, claims not to support either the current government or the opposition.
A 50% majority plus one vote is needed to win the election.
If none of the candidates reach this threshold, a second round of elections must be organised within two weeks.
