According to Chatel, the subjects of geography and history emerge strengthened from the school reform of the Lycées.
In an interview published in the Sunday newspaper "Journal du dimanche", the national minister of education Luc Chatel stated that the subjects of geography and history emerge strengthened from the school reform of the Lycées, even if they are not taught obligatorily in the terminale (12th school year).
"Pupils in the 11th grade now have all four lessons per week and the same programme," confirms Mr Chatel.
For the minister, "this hypocrisy must be overcome", because according to him, "the scientific profile is no longer a scientific profile", but on the whole a concentration of "the best students".
"The economic, social and literary profile (ES and L) must not become a sub-profile of the scientific," he continued. He underlined: "I have not yet heard many historians and intellectuals who have been outraged by the lack of historical geographical education in the terminals on technical Lyceums."
On Saturday, an IFOP poll published by the Humanité found that nearly seven out of ten French (69%) were critical of the government ’ s plan to cut the compulsory history and geography curriculum in Terminale S. Many teachers and intellectuals also criticized the plan, as did the left and some right-wing representatives.
The Minister replied that there was no question of limiting the philosophy of the Terminal S program.
Luc Chatel also defended the educational reform for teachers, while 16 organisations (students and trade unions) called for Tuesday to protest against the project, which in their opinion is sacrificing the educational training of future teachers.
The Minister stated that in Master 2 (M2) they undergo a subject-specific aptitude test at the beginning of the year and at the end of the year an admission test, during which their teaching skills are tested.
They also carry out internships during the year at the M2 and then teach as an internship teacher one year before the students.
He went on to say: "If you add all the internships offered before the performance test, you will get even more hours you spent before the students, i.e. more than 300 hours."
The minister finally stated that he wanted to offer "the individual right to education" - a "thing that does not exist in popular education."
He reconfirmed that he wants to abolish the school card "by 2012".
15 minutes for the climate at the "Ecole Normale Supérieure"
Fifteen minutes to talk about the operation at the Copenhagen Summit: this is the challenge faced by Jean Jouzel, Vice-President of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, at the Ecole Normale Supérieure in Rue d'Ulm in Paris on Saturday morning.
According to an AFP journalist, Nobel Peace Prize winner Jean Jouzel opened the first of the "Ernest" conferences, at which experts turn to the audience for fifteen minutes each with filmed contributions.
One wants to do something to reach people and make them want to know more, said Edouard Hannezo, 22 years old and one of the organizers of the day, on the sidelines of the conference. The name of this event comes from the name that the students gave to the fish in the basin of the school.
"Among the experts, about twenty participants were chosen, also according to their charisma," he specifies.
"You can talk for hours on end about global warming, but the key goals can also be set out in a few minutes," said Jean Jouzel of AFP, who gave a free speech in front of some 50 people only with the help of slides.
"This is part of our role as scientists," he said, hoping that the audience would see that "the Copenhagen conference is based on an absolutely serious scientific dossier."
The videos shot at these conferences will be available online on the school ’ s website from 15 December.
The next "Ernest" day is scheduled for February and will take place every two months thereafter.
Late payment: angry prison guards, actions planned
On Friday, the penitentiary unions called for a general day of action to ensure that the bonuses and overtime paid until January for budgetary reasons are transferred before the Christmas holidays.
The 2nd Penitentiary Union ("FO" Penitentiary Workers' Union ") called on employees who are not on duty to demonstrate in front of the penitentiary on Tuesday morning and block it in order to draw attention to the" theft of what they are entitled to ".
The 3rd Penitentiary Union ("CGT" Pénitentiaire ") called for" a strong mobilization in the various prisons ", on which the non-payment of the overtime, night and Sunday and holiday surcharges incurred in October is branded as" shameful and unacceptable ".
The first union of penitentiary officers, the Autonomous Federal Penitentiary Union (UFAP / UNSA), called for "general mobilizations (...) to show dissatisfaction and anger."
The management of the penitentiary and the Ministry of Justice said that overtime in 2009 had increased sharply and not all of it was budgeted for, but they guarantee that the remaining claims will be paid in January.
As reported by the Ministry of Justice in the evening, Michele Alliot and Marie sent a letter to the penal unions, guaranteeing that the payment will be made next month.
"I am well aware of the efforts made by the staff to keep our penal system functioning and to modernise it", the Minister of Justice informs in this letter.
"I have instructed the management of the penitentiary to take immediate measures to ensure that such a situation, which has arisen as a result of a lack of evaluation of overtime, is not repeated in the future," added Ms Alliot.
The December wage is thus meagre, except for the management personnel, which will benefit from high service and target premiums, explains the UFAP / UNSA, for which the "budgetary constraints" must be used.
