The cradle of the dinosaurs
Tawa hallae looked like many other carnivorous dinosaurs: The two meter long and 1.5 meter tall animal ran on two strong hind legs, had an elongated skull with sharp, curved teeth, short arms with sickle claws and a long tail.
If the species had lived a few million years later, it would have been nothing special.
But Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body characteristics, report Sterling Nesbitt from the University of Texas in Austin and colleagues in the journal Science from Thursday.
The animal lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which at that time lay in a dry zone of the supercontinent Pangaea at the equator.
Tawa opens a new window on the early evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
He shows us a lot about the kinship, the spread and the characteristics of the early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other palaeontologists began excavating the Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
We have sometimes found a dozen dinosaurs in a day, which is unprecedented for deposits from the Triassic, reports team member Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History.
The researchers quickly identified some of the bones as new species.
During the excavation they gathered the remains of five individuals.
Finds confirm theories of Dino ’ s early history
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt, it is an extraordinary find: "Dinosaur fossils from the Triassic are extremely rare, mostly you only find single fragments."
Other dinosaur experts do not necessarily share the enthusiasm.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the early history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander from the University of Bonn.
According to current doctrine, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
Many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, however, which is why the assignment of these original dinosaurs is usually controversial.
The experts, for example, discuss when the lizards split into their three most important lines of evolution: the carnivorous theropods, which later included the Tyrannosaurus rex, the Velociraptor and also the birds, the four-legged sauropods known as "longnecks" and their relatives, and the herbivorous ornithischia, which included the species Triceratops and Stegosaurus.
According to the analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa hallae is an original theropod.
It has an interesting combination of primitive and advanced properties, says Nesbitt.
On the skull of Tawa hallae, for example, the researchers found evidence of air bags similar to those of the descendants of the theropods, the birds.
Thanks to the air bags, birds breathe more efficiently than mammals.
In Tawa hallae, the bones of the spine were also apparently partially filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropod with air bags, says Randall Irmis.
Since the related line of the huge Sauropods later also had airbags and lightweight construction, the common ancestor of both groups probably had already produced this useful innovation.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs known to date lived in South America, the researchers conclude that the lizards first appeared there.
According to this, the three lines of development separated early and spread from South America over all continents, which at that time still formed a single land mass as the supercontinent Pangea.
This is supported by the fact that the team found the remains of two other, not very closely related theropods together with Tawa hallae.
The researchers argue that the three cannot come from a common, immigrant ancestor.
We believe there have been at least three waves of migration to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, a co-author of the science study.
Of course, there are also contradictions.
An even older species, Silesaurus, which belongs to a sister group of dinosaurs, lived in present-day Poland, says Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
In his opinion a distorted picture could arise, because in South America simply a lot of primitive dino-fossils have been preserved, while on other continents hardly anything is to be found.
It is still a mystery how the dinosaurs managed to evolve from a relatively rare tribe of reptiles to the dominant agricultural animals of the Middle Ages.
During the Triassic the dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, for example with the ancestors of today's crocodiles and the pterosaurs and with numerous other lizards.
Towards the end of the Triassic the dinosaurs spread all over the world and developed many new species, while the relationship at the border of the Triassic to the Jurassic died out.
Success story did not last forever
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There may have been a mass extinction that the dinosaurs accidentally survived, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted so that they could beat the competition out of the field.
The success story did not last forever.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact helped a group of animals to bloom that had also developed in the Triassic and had been in the shadows ever since: the mammals.
