Some see pictures in an awake state and hear voices that others do not see or hear.
The boundaries between imagination and reality are blurring, not only in the case of the mentally ill and drug addicts.
As long as it happens in sleep, everything is fine.
When we lie with our eyes closed in our dark rooms, we are free to indulge in the wildest imaginations and fantasies.
In the modern Western world, however, those who experience dream-like states, see and hear things that others do not see or hear, are usually considered crazy or drug addicted, at least as eccentrics.
But such images and voices do not only arise in mentally ill people or in drug intoxication.
Our imagination is to blame: the same neural processes that enable us to design houses, paint pictures, or write novels sometimes cause the boundaries between dream, delusion, and reality to blur.
Dreamlike altered states of waking consciousness can occur in different forms, in the best case we call them visions, in the worst case delusion.
Even if triggers and effects may differ, the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the drug experiences of the New Age, prophet Carlos Castaneda, shamanic rapture states, psychoses and hallucinations can be traced back to similar processes.
Hallucinations or delusions occur when the balance of the neuronal messenger substances of the brain - above all dopamine, norepinephrine, serotonin and acetylcholine - is derailed and the interaction of different parts of the brain is disturbed.
Complex hallucinations and delusional thoughts very often occur during schizophrenic psychosis.
Gravity has no more power over him
The connection between delusion and dream has occupied philosophers and physicians since antiquity.
Aristotle understood hallucinations as a form of dream in an awake state, Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, stated in 1861 that "there is a great similarity between insanity and dream states", for Sigmund Freud the dream was even "a psychosis, with all the inconsistencies, delusions, illusions of such a state".
It is autumn 2001, when Henning T. turns into a cartoon character.
His body is two-dimensional and colourful.
Gravity has no more power over him, he floats on the ceiling.
He feels a kick.
Behind him winged devils with blood-red, distorted grimaces, dotting their teeth.
They chase him, kick him with heavy, flaming boots, throw him against the walls, he feels the pain all over his body.
Loud, vicious voices roar from walls and radio.
He can no longer bear the voices that insult and insult him.
Henning T. pulls two cables out of the stereo, ties them to a loop and fastens them to a hook on the ceiling.
He climbs onto a loudspeaker and puts the noose around his neck.
Jump.
The noose comes off.
That should be a lesson for you, the voices scream in a choir that tears apart the drums, "Go to the clinic and let yourself be healed!"
Today Henning T. is 40 years old, he experienced six acute psychosis, the last one was 2 years ago, the first one nearly 20 years ago.
It was triggered by LSD.
His diagnosis is schizoaffective, paranoid psychosis, moreover, he is manic-depressed, he takes medicine against depression, mania, schizophrenia.
He has learned to live with his illness, he has been married for three years.
In the psychosis, he says, I have experienced the worst fear and the deepest despair.
The illusions are cruel reality
About one percent of the population suffers from schizophrenia at least once in their lives, and psychiatric hospitals treat it as the second most common disease after depression.
In an acute schizophrenic psychosis, patients are usually no longer able to distinguish between the inner and outer worlds; they get into an overexcited state that can lead to hallucinations, delusions of size, relationships or persecution.
Listening to voices is particularly common - voices that command, comment or dialogue.
Optical hallucinations are also not uncommon.
The affected person is no longer able to separate important from unimportant things, the brain can no longer filter out disturbing signals, and consciousness is flooded with impressions.
Like the dream, psychosis opens the floodgates to a flood of ideas and fantasies that come from deeper layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is subject-centered, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, senior physician at the Clinic for General Psychiatry at Heidelberg University Hospital.
The schizophrenic is at the centre of what is happening, everything has a meaning directed at him.
At the same time he falls into a passive role, he is overwhelmed by events, as in a dream, and cannot actively shape them.
Schizophrenics therefore often feel threatened, controlled and manipulated.
They are usually not able to match reality, the illusions are cruel reality, awakening is excluded.
To have experienced a hallucination once in a lifetime
Unlike in dreams, says Fuchs, "the sensual and spatial structure of reality, which is perceived in the psychosis, remains fundamentally intact."
The delusional thoughts and hallucinations are rooted in reality, the alienation of the experience takes place in the real framework.
Exactly why our brain beats anomalies is still a mystery to researchers.
States of emergency can cause any person to lose touch with reality for a short time, says Fuchs.
But not everyone will develop a psychosis.
There seems to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but twin studies have shown that genes are not the only determinants.
Researchers assume that there is minimal brain damage in those affected.
We suspect that the neuronal maturation of the brain is disturbed at an early stage of development, for example, by a viral disease of the mother during pregnancy, explains Fuchs.
But it remains a mystery how the disturbance of the neural system comes about, which furthermore does not manifest itself for many years at first.
Also environmental influences play a role - stress or traumatic experiences can be triggers for a psychosis, if the disposition is present.
Hallucinogenic drugs can also cause psychosis, as they interfere with the transmitter system.
When our brain is running hot
The crazy thing is that psychotics suffer from their hallucinations and swallow expensive drugs to get rid of them, while others spend money on drugs to get them, says Lübeck psychology professor Erich Kasten.
Whether illusions are perceived as pleasant or unpleasant is often only a matter of standpoint.
Kasten has been collecting reports about hallucinations and deceptions for ten years, last year he evaluated his results in the book "The Unreal World in Our Head".
Hallucinations belong to the typical side effects of psychosis, but also of surprisingly many other diseases.
In addition to mental disorders such as borderlines or depression, this often includes diseases such as migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis or Alzheimer ’ s and brain trauma.
Surprisingly, even the brains of healthy people hallucinate under certain conditions.
Hallucinations, according to Kasten, are composed of memory contents that are usually retained.
They occur when areas of the brain in which sensory perception is processed are overactive or inhibited too little; when our brain is running hot or when stimulation is missing.
Drugs can cause this condition in the same way as brain damage or psychosis.
But also attraction, stress, lovesickness or other mental states of emergency.
In recent studies, up to one third of respondents stated that they had experienced hallucination at least once in their lives.
In the summer of 2005, Sarah K. is 16 years old. She lives in a small town in Mecklenburg, Western Pomerania, and attends grammar school there.
A normal girl, actually.
If there weren ’ t the images and voices.
In the interval it can happen that a lanky boy with long, dark hair addresses it.
When it answers it, classmates look at it in surprise - nobody else sees or hears this boy.
They think the shy girl is a spooky daydreamer, but Sarah K. doesn ’ t dream, she knows.
She is awake, she hears and sees this boy, just as she hears and sees the girl in the bench next to her.
She can even feel his presence, at least for a moment.
This is a pleasant feeling, she likes the boy.
Am I crazy? she sometimes wonders.
But she knows that this boy and the other illusions are not real and disappear again.
At night the apparitions are usually frightening
Often the illusions are also a burden.
When she sits in the classroom, she sometimes cannot follow the subject matter, because the teacher is introducing a new classmate in her eyes and ears, while he explains mathematical equations audibly and visibly on the blackboard for everyone else.
At night, the apparitions are usually frightening.
When she waits in her dark room for sleep, which is far too rare and far too late, she often cannot tell whether she is awake or already dreaming, whether the pictures she sees, the grimaces or the girl with the bleeding cuts on her arms and legs, are created in front of her open or closed eyes.
Leave me alone, she screams at the figures.
Parents and friends do not tell her about it, they would consider her crazy.
Autumn 2009. Sarah K. is 20 years old today.
She graduated last year and lives with her boyfriend.
A year ago, hallucinations stopped.
Ever since she contacted the psychologist Kasten on the Internet, she has known that she is not crazy.
Delusion is also a work of art of despair
If someone is socially isolated or suffering from irritation, he will most likely have hallucinations after a while, says Kasten.
I suspect that the brain is then underoccupied and takes care of its own entertainment.
Sarah K., an only child, was afraid of other children as a little girl, often playing alone.
Her hallucinations began when she learned at the age of 13 that the man she calls Daddy, since she can think, is not her biological father.
Since the same areas of the brain that process real impressions and sounds are active in visual and acoustic hallucinations, it is difficult for sufferers like Sarah K. to distinguish between illusions and reality. "Every experience," says Kasten, "takes place in the brain, reality is reflected there.
Hallucinations are also images that make the brain appear so real. "
Kasten also values nocturnal dream images as a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people do not differ fundamentally from those of an acute psychosis.
In contrast to schizophrenics, psychologically healthy people are able to recognize their illusions as unreal.
Kasten therefore advises his patients to value hallucinations as a special ability.
Border state between dream and hallucination
In our too much consciousness-centered world, imaginary experience is unfortunately usually pathologized, says Michael Schmidt Degenhard, Professor in Heidelberg and head physician of the Department of Psychiatry and Psychotherapy of Florence ’ s Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a serious, painful illness, but it also contains positive, creative elements - delusion is also a work of art out of despair.
Schmidt ’ s Degenhard has researched the so-called oneiroid experience, a special form of dream-like altered wakefulness.
Oneiroids are highly complex, detailed, quasi-dreams, which the experiencing person believes to be real and which he cannot differentiate from the waking state in retrospect.
The oneiroid state of consciousness arises in trauma- or disease-related extreme situations, for example in polyradiculitis, patients who experience motor paralysis in full consciousness.
When a person is threatened by loss of himself and the world, for example through permanent, total incapacity to move, he replaces the life-threatening real situation with his own imaginary world, which is decoupled from reality, says Schmidt, Degenhard.
A kind of borderline state between dream and hallucination.
Since coping with a situation is not possible in reality, a change of world takes place, but the real situation is visualized in the imagination.
An intensive form of creating meaning and giving meaning in an intolerable situation, which enables us humans their own creative ability not to get lost in a nothingness of loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in the memory
The Zurich art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen also describes his oneiroid adventures in his book "Herzwechsel" as a rescue operation for the soul.
He is 49 years old when his consciousness travels for days after a heart valve operation followed by a heart transplant, while his body is condemned to motionlessness in the intensive care unit.
Claussen dives into a self-created world, visits foreign times and places: he experiences himself as a bed-ridden old man, on board a train sanatorium, a robot watches over his health.
In the early Middle Ages, he lived among nobles who produced intoxicants from blood.
Abducted by a Greek on a motorcycle to his home country, surfs with his hospital bed in the firn snow of the Alps and meets a Korean mafioso.
It is completely absorbed in the imagined event, everything is real, even later in the memory.
For Claussen, these inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream.
Dream is a different state, he describes his experience.
In contrast to that, the memories from mental journeys are still very clear to me after years and in minor details.
More clearly and intensively even than really experienced.
The intensity of this experience goes beyond the horizon of our other life-world experiences, says psychiatrist Schmidt Degenhard.
Ultimately, oneiroids, psychosis, hallucinations, and drug intoxication show how fragile our inner images of outer reality are in waking.
Any change in the state of consciousness, summarizes the psychologist Kasten, "can lead to a deformation of what we call reality."
An experience that can also be enriching.
