75% of working mothers have problems at work because of their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially among the younger women who want to have children.
This is the conclusion of the study "Fertility and careers of women in Spain" carried out by CSIC in collaboration with the Institute for Women.
The survey of 9,737 women aged between 15 and 75 leaves no room for doubt: 75% of working women see their career opportunities on the labour market restricted by motherhood.
The study reveals that there are big differences in the decision to start a family and the number of children depending on whether the women work or not and if so, what kind of job they do.
Those who do not do any other work outside the home, who only work part-time or do not have a permanent contract of employment are more likely to become mothers and have more children.
In contrast, women with permanent employment, especially in the public sector, postpone the establishment of a family and motherhood and therefore have fewer children.
"On average, women in the 35-49 age group who have a permanent job do not have their first child until 3.7 years after they have moved in, a figure that increases to 4.1 years for women with a permanent job who have taken longer to do so and who have moved in and have had their first child much later.
In addition, the type of work also has a major impact on motherhood, although less than the calendar in terms of conception ”, explains CSIC ’ s researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that must be taken into account when women get married and when they have their first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of education, the higher the age at the time of marriage and the higher the first child.
This difference could also be seen in women of the same age.
For example, women in the group between the ages of 35 and 49, depending on whether they only have a lower secondary education or a higher education, became mothers for the first time on average at 25.1 or 32.1.
There is also another difference between women, depending on their level of education.
Whereas the main graduation women get married before their first permanent employment and have their first child, the middle or high school graduates do it the other way around and first look for a permanent job and then get married and then have their first child, states Delgado.
