After almost two years, the vans market finally begins to see some light at the end of the dark tunnel.
The 9,425 vehicles registered in Spain in November represent an increase of 12.6% compared to 2008 and, more importantly, the first increase after 22 consecutive months of steady decline, according to the figures presented by the Anfac Manufacturers Association and the Ganvam Automobile Dealers Association.
However, these good figures are currently to be enjoyed with great caution, as the reference figures used for comparison are from November 2008, which was a particularly bad sales year with a decrease of 60% compared to the previous year.
However, it must be borne in mind that, apart from the increase last month, total approvals for these 11 months are still 40% below the sales figures of the previous financial year.
Since January, a total of 95,853 vehicles have been sold, but this figure includes all the vehicles that make up the small van market: car derivatives, pick ups, vans, small vans and lighter vans / chassis.
Furthermore, there are still the same thunderclouds in the sky, which affect demand the most, because even if some of the vehicles are bought by private individuals, the majority of the sales go to small and medium-sized enterprises, which in almost 100% of all cases make the purchase with a third party financing.
In addition to these restrictions, which are the consequence of the credit institutions losing money, other factors must be included, such as the increase in the rate of unemployment or the continuation of the bad economic situation.
In this panorama, unlike cars, financial support for the purchase of a 2000E plan vehicle has done little to help.
