Support for braking manoeuvres in critical situations is now mandatory
As was the case with the ABS anti-lock braking system and as is currently happening with the ESP stability control system, the emergency braking systems must become mandatory equipment in European cars.
In fact, they are already compulsory for all newly registered passenger cars and light vans, and the remaining vehicles are subject to a waiting period until the end of February 2011.
The aim of the measure adopted by the European Union is to improve the protection of pedestrians, but due to their functioning, these braking systems can also help prevent many rear-end collisions.
The task of the Emergency Brake Assist is to exert more pressure on the brakes in the event of a critical braking manoeuvre, which the system detects based on the braking power applied to the brake pedal by the driver.
However, this system does not apply this pressure to the end.
According to a study commissioned by the component manufacturer for the Bosch vehicles, one-third of the drivers involved in an accident were no longer able to press the brake pedal before the collision and half of them had not braked at full force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The braking aid, on the other hand, intervenes with maximum force in the braking system, thereby reducing the braking time and thus the braking distance covered by a car during braking.
According to an EU study, up to 1,100 pedestrian deaths could be prevented each year if all cars were equipped with this type of emergency braking system.
There would be even fewer accidents - one in four accidents involving personal injury is expected to be prevented - once the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems became popular.
The vehicle is then equipped with a system that detects obstacles (via radar or a camera) and warns the driver, while at the same time exerting slight pressure on the brakes.
If the driver responds, the system helps him to increase the pressure on the brake pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not respond to the warning and even if the collision is inevitable, the Brake Assist will apply maximum pressure on the brakes to minimise the damage.
