No single accident is the same, and calculating the cost of the parts and hours worked can be a lengthy and complicated task.
The manual calculation of repair costs of between 20,000 and 30,000 euros, including parts and working hours, can take up to two or three hours.
On the other hand it is a matter of minutes with the support of the newest informatics tools.
That is why almost 100% of surveyors use this type of system.
Accident and repair evaluation service providers collect the information they receive from manufacturers in order to process it and offer it to their customers in the form of a useful programme.
In Spain, Audatex, part of the American Solera Group, is the market leader; 80% of all appraisals are carried out with its products.
The other two companies competing with each other in the evaluation and report preparation market are GtMotive and Eurotax.
Working with the data provided by the manufacturers is anything but easy.
According to Eduardo Velázquez, Sales Manager of Audatex, the company works with 63 manufacturers and importers, each of whom provides information in a different format.
In addition, the amount of data to be processed is steadily increasing, to the point that in the last five years even more versions, variants and engines have been launched than in the entire fifteen years before.
As soon as a new car enters the market, the companies start their work.
It is a laborious task, because each of the thousands and thousands of vehicle parts must be catagolized and its price entered.
In addition, an "intelligent" graphic image is created of each model, on which one can "click" on different parts of the vehicle.
If this is a much sold model, the work can be completed in a week, if the procedure proceeds quickly.
If it is a less common car, it can take up to three or four months. Currently, 99.2% of cars sold in Spain are fully informed by Audatex.
Among the more exclusive models, for example, they have information on Porsche models, but not on Ferrari or Lamborghini.
In terms of the number of vehicles on the roads, it is over 99%.
In order to carry out documentation work and to produce databases, Audatex has eight centres located all over the world (Spain, France, Germany, the United States, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan), each of which specialises in specific trademarks.
The national headquarters is located in Alcobendas (Madrid).
There, more than a hundred technicians (usually mechanical specialists) work simultaneously with three computer screens.
Audatex invests 90 million Euros annually in the development of these databases.
Every month they collect 2.5 million data and their customers receive updates every other day.
The development of this enormous flow of information enables companies to use it in different ways and thus offer different products.
The most common use is for repairs and repairs, but depending on the country, there are also tools for managing scrap or calculating the file or residual value of a car.
The only company that has a guide that informs about the value of used cars in Spain is Eurotax.
Audatex does not offer this service in Spain but in the United States.
When reviewing the products that Audatex offers, it is easy to get an overview of the type of support that it provides to industry experts.
This company offers ten different tools, the star of which is AudaPlus, a standard solution for assessing accidents for the assessors.
It includes vehicles, motorcycles and light and heavy industrial vehicles.
In addition to the cost of the parts, it includes the repair times estimated by the manufacturer or the painting prices.
This tool is paid for according to the intended use, i.e. for each report.
It will be most expensive for customers who rarely use it a maximum of ten times a month, namely 5.75 euros per month.
On the other hand, any insurance company that produces thousands of reports negotiates the price with Audatex.
With other products, such as AudaVIN, a vehicle and the equipment it ran off the assembly line can be fully identified solely on the basis of the chassis number.
AudaGlass deals with the vehicle windows, and AudaSubastas is a service on the Internet that is open to the specialist market and can be used for vehicles that have been declared a total loss.
Your statistical service is very useful in identifying trends, performing geodemographic analyses, or obtaining information on brand and model deviations.
For example, it can be used to investigate how many models of a particular car brand had to go to the workshop because of a breakdown or how many of them were involved in a serious accident over a certain period of time.
Gt Motive is the only Spanish company dedicated to the development of this type of computer tools.
It distributes, among others, Gt Estimate, which is also intended for appraisers and provides digital images, access to parts or prices and official working hours of the manufacturer in the same way.
Gt Motive is a company of the Einsa Group, founded in 1971 as a provider of services and solutions for damage, breakdown and maintenance of vehicles.
GT ’ s Expert Guidance Guide is a reference product on the market.
They cooperate with 24,000 users in workshops, 3,100 experts and 53 insurance companies.
Its business volume has increased by 20% annually in the last three years and in 2008 the turnover amounted to 10.8 million euros.
At the beginning of last year, they also started to enter the international market with the opening of an office in Paris.
Audatex, on the other hand, was founded in Germany in 1966 and set up in Spain in 1979.
According to the company ’ s sources, 62% of its business is in Europe and the rest of the world, with the remaining 38% in North and South America. They work with 900 insurance companies and 33,000 workshops, 3,000 of which are in Spain.
Total sales in the world of the Solera Group (Audatex, Sidexa, Informex ABZ, Hollander and IMS) amounted to 557 million dollars, 3.35 more than in 2008.
In this country, the company has revenues of 19.1 million euros, 7.2% more than in the previous year.
In 2005, the Solera Group was worth $1 billion on the stock market, and today its shares are traded at $2.4 billion.
They have been listed on the New York Stock Exchange since 2007 and are part of the reference index Standard & Poor's.
Auction of Accident Cars on the Internet
Last October, the Solera Autoonline group bought a platform on the Internet for the sale of accidental vehicles and motorcycles.
This purchase meant the payment of 59.5 million euros for 85% of the company ’ s capital, which could increase to the remaining 15% next year.
The purpose of this purchase was to offer its customers more services and value creation, with the opportunity to gain access to a vast international market.
This appraisal and purchase service is aimed exclusively at industry professionals, such as insurance companies, appraisers, car rental companies, workshops, scrap yards and car dealers, who must register before their activities.
This platform was created 1996 in Germany and administers more than 650.000 operations in completely Europe, 500,000 of it in Germany alone.
Its main markets are Spain, Greece, Poland and Turkey.
The website currently has more than 1,500 registered sellers and 4,000 appraisers.
Every day 3,000 ads are managed and 100 new ads are added to the Spanish market every day.
According to Spanish legislation, a vehicle whose chassis number has been unregistered may no longer drive on the roads, but certain non-damaged parts may be used as spare parts.
On the other hand, cars with historical value may be re-registered, even if they have been registered out after difficult administrative procedures.
Estimate of the workshop in four steps
Audatex makes sure that the user receives an estimate in just four steps: identification of the vehicle, search for the spare part, preparation and preparation of an estimate.
The easy handling of these systems is a fundamental condition, especially in order to convince the older specialists, who are usually more or less opposed to the use of these new computer technologies.
The database comprises 1,034 vehicles, of which 666 are passenger cars, 109 off-road vehicles, 137 motorcycles, 78 vans and 44 trucks.
Of course you need a computer with internet connection.
After the model to be repaired has been identified by the chassis number, a graphic of the respective model appears and then the required spare part is selected.
The user can include variables such as the price of the working hours, surcharges or discounts and then have the estimate printed and passed on to his customer.
However, AudaTaller is not a tool for evaluation like AudaPlus, but rather a reference catalogue.
The main difference between the two systems is that the workshop oriented one does not include estimated working hours.
The cost of using this tool is 350 euros per year, an amount that the customer can easily pay.
At present, Audatex is working on offering these images in three-dimensional format.
This is an innovation that car mechanics have been waiting for a long time, because with it, for example, you can select a door and then turn the image completely over to look at the inside.
